<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="270">Ann. Rep. Natl. Mus. Canada</emphasis>
50: 116. 1928; Rauschert in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="270">Feddes Repert.</emphasis>
88: 318. 1977) to treat it as ambiguous. However, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Widén’s">Widen's</normalizedToken>
typification has established the usage of the name and seems to have been accepted by later authors. See detailed reviews by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Widén">Widen</normalizedToken>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="270">l.c.</emphasis>
: 68-71) and Edgar &amp; Forde (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="270">New Zealand J. Bot.</emphasis>
29: 154. 1991).
</paragraph>
